      My research goal is to improve software quality through program analysis and testing. I want to make techniques more accurate, more automated, more user-friendly, and, when needed, more efficient.  All these can result in less cost to Software Engineering. 
    -->
My research interests are in Software Engineering and Programming
Languages, with a focus on improving software reliability. Software bugs
are inevitable as software is mostly written by humans. My research 
focuses at improving software quality assurance tasks,
including bug prevention, bug finding, bug diagnosis, and code
repair. All these can result in less cost to Software Engineering.
   
    
  <hr>
  
  Previously: I obtained my PhD from the University of
    Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (<a href="http://www.cs.illinois.edu" target="_blank">UIUC</a>) in 2007<!--, advised by <a href="http://mir.cs.illinois.edu/marinov/" target="_blank">Darko Marinov</a>,--> and my BS and MS degrees from the Federal University of Pernambuco, Brazil (1996 and 2001, respectively).  I spent a sabbatical year at Georgia Tech from June 2015 to July 2016.
  
